                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"><certainty match=".." locus="name"/></gap><orig>αν</orig><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"><certainty match=".." locus="name"/></gap>
                </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
               </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Intraduisible.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Not usefully translatable.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Intraducibile.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>غير قابل للترجمة بشكل جيد</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Too small to allow a ceramological datation, this fragment was found in a sounding that evidenced the building of the small temple with double oikos
                once considered to be dedicated to the Dioscuri, dated about the middle of the fifth century BC (see <bibl><ptr target="#bacchielli1981"/>, pp.
                 <citedRange>53-62</citedRange></bibl>). This fits well the poor rests of the graffito, which might be a trademark rather than a 
                    more carefully cut dedication.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
